The Questions

1.

a)

Amazon_merge %>% summarise(min = min(star_rating), mean = mean(star_rating), median = median(star_rating), max = max(star_rating), sd = sd(star_rating), IQR = IQR(star_rating)) %>% kable()
min mean median max sd IQR
1 4.454072 5 5 1.025113 1

The summary statistics here shows that the minimum number of stars a customer has given for a book review is 1 and the maximum is 5. Average number of stars given for any book is 4.45. The median which is the middle number in a data set is the same as the maximum number of stars in this data frame. We will be able to see a peak on the right side. The standard deviation tells us the distance from the mean. This means that 68% of the reviews lie between 4.45 - 1.02 and 4.45 + 1.02 stars. The IQR is the inter quartile range (Q3 - Q1). The IQR is 1 which shows us that the difference between the 75th percentile and the 25th percentile is not very big. The third quartile is rating 5 and first quartile is rating 4. This means that 50% of the data lies between star ratings 4 and 5.

b)
The data frame product shows the number of times each product has been reviewed. We are then filtering out the products that have been reviewed 100 times or more in the data frame product1. Over100 data frame is the result of filtering out all the product parents with 100 or more reviews along with all the other information that corresponds to each product_parent.
mean_star_rating is grouping the duplicated product_parent and thus removing the duplicated product_parent. We are also finding the mean and standard deviation of the star ratings. sorted_star_rating has sorted the product_parent in decreasing order of the average star rating.
Using the inner_join function, we added the frequency of reviews to the sorted_star_rating data frame.
Top10 gets the 10 products that have the top 10 star ratings.

product<- data.frame(table(Amazon_merge$product_parent))
product1 <- product[product$Freq > 99, ]

Over100 <- Amazon_merge %>% filter(product_parent %in% product1$Var1)

mean_star_rating <- Over100 %>% group_by(product_parent) %>% summarise(mean_stars = mean(star_rating), sd_stars = sd(star_rating))
sorted_star_rating <- mean_star_rating %>% arrange(desc(mean_stars))  

names(product1)[1]<-"product_parent"
withFreq <- inner_join(sorted_star_rating, product1, by = "product_parent")

Top10 <- withFreq[1:10, ]
Top10 %>% kable()

Here we can see that the median is much lesser than the mean and therefore the peak of the data lies to the right side. Since the median is way lower than average, we will consider the median and not the mean for more accuracy of data. The inter quartile range, IQR, is pretty big and therefore there are no sudden changes in the graphs and it is rather gradual.
We are then doing a t-test to test our hypothesis that the greater the length of the review, the lesser the star rating.
We first found the length of the reviews for each product. We then divided the review lengths into two groups via the median of the review length. We then perform the t-test on the star rating and the two groups of review length:

summary(Amazon_merge$review_length)
##   review_body     
##  Min.   :    1.0  
##  1st Qu.:  102.0  
##  Median :  190.0  
##  Mean   :  493.5  
##  3rd Qu.:  474.0  
##  Max.   :48604.0
Amazon_merge$review_length_groups <- cut(Amazon_merge$review_length, 
                                         breaks = c(1, 192, 48604), 
                                         labels = c("Short Review", "Long Review"))
table(Amazon_merge$review_length_groups)
## 
## Short Review  Long Review 
##       227438       223768
t.test(star_rating ~ review_length_groups, data = Amazon_merge, alternative = "greater")
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  star_rating by review_length_groups
## t = 76.687, df = 432130, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is greater than 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.2279452       Inf
## sample estimates:
## mean in group Short Review  mean in group Long Review 
##                   4.569518                   4.336576

Our hypothesis in this was that shorter reviews have greater star ratings than longer reviews. The null hypothesis says that there is no difference in the ratings for short and long reviews. Through the t-test we see that the results are significant as the p-value is lesser than 0.05. This implies that null hypothesis is rejected and there is a difference between the two groups of review lengths.

2.

We looked into the relationship between length of reviews and the star ratings. In order to do this, we grouped the data frame by star rating and got the median length for the reviews. In this graph we can see that shorter reviews have higher star ratings, with five star reviews being the shortest in length.

Amazon_merge_reviews <- Amazon_merge %>% group_by(star_rating) %>% summarise(median_length = median(review_length, na.rm = TRUE))

ggplot(Amazon_merge_reviews, aes(star_rating, median_length)) + 
  geom_col(fill = "cornflower blue") + theme_classic() + ggtitle("Review Lengths for Star Ratings") + labs(x = "Star Rating", y = "Review Length Median")

We decided to further look into the relationship between helpful votes and length of review over the different star ratings. We looked at how many helpful votes a review got based on its length for each of the star ratings, which we have facet wrapped.

ggplot(Amazon_merge, aes(helpful_votes, review_length)) + 
  geom_point(alpha = 0.7, color = "coral") + 
  facet_wrap(~factor(star_rating)) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") + 
  ggtitle("Number of Helpful Votes for Review Lengths of Different Star Ratings") + 
  labs(x = "Number of helpful votes", y = "Length of Review")

From the graph we can see that reviews with star ratings 4 and 5 are much longer than the other reviews. This could probably be because of the fact that people are more opinionated when it comes to extremely good products and they probably critically analyze while wiritng their reviews. Reviewers may praise a 4 or 5 star rated book much more than any other rated book and will therefore give more detail in their reviews.Books rated 2, 3 and 4 are pretty much the same in terms of length of reviews as well as number of helpful votes. It is also observed that reviews of star rating 5 have most number of helpful votes. This makes sense, as customers are interested in buying the best products and will therefore fins 5 star rated books the most helpful.

3.

Our hypothesis is that longer reviews get more number of helpful votes irrespective of whether the purchasers are verified or not.
In order to test this, we will look at:
1. correlation between length of reviews and number of helpful votes
- corr between helpful_votes and review_length
2. summary statistics of helpful_votes to get basic information on the number of helpful votes like the minimum, maximum, mean, median, standard deviation and IQR
3. t-test on review length and number of helpful votes
- t-test(review_length, helpful_votes)
4. t-test on number of helpful votes and verified purchase
- t-test(verified_purchase, helpful_votes)
5. regression analysis on number of helpful votes, verified purchases and length of review
- lm(helpful_votes ~ review_length + verified purchase)

cor(Amazon_merge$helpful_votes, Amazon_merge$review_length)

The summary of number of helpful votes and length of review gives us further insight into these variables.

t.test(helpful_votes ~ review_length_groups, data = Amazon_merge, alternative = "less")
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  helpful_votes by review_length_groups
## t = -63.725, df = 241100, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is less than 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##       -Inf -2.242769
## sample estimates:
## mean in group Short Review  mean in group Long Review 
##                  0.5011344                  2.8033276

Through the t-test we can see that shorter reviews do have lesser number of helpful votes as the p-value here is less than 0.05. The result is significant and null hypothesis is rejected. Our hypothesis suggested that short reviews had a lesser mean than long reviews.

t.test(helpful_votes ~ verified_purchase, data = Amazon_merge)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  helpful_votes by verified_purchase
## t = 29.936, df = 146330, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  1.504608 1.715429
## sample estimates:
## mean in group N mean in group Y 
##        2.809206        1.199187

Through this t-test, we see that the p-value is less than 0.05 and null hypothesis is rejected. Thus, contrary to our hypothesis, this shows that there is a diiference between the non-verified group and verified group means.
